% Motivation
Students of the Latin American states have several \emph{theories} to explain the causes and consequences of state capacities. Scholars also have countless alternatives to \emph{measure} state capacities. However, there exist a huge deficit. On the one hand, most state formation theories (just to name a few) are situated during precolonial times,\footnote{\citet{Mahoney:2010aa}.} during early\footnote{See \citet[]{Kurtz:2013aa} and \citet[]{Soifer2015a}.} or late\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} independent Latin America. On the other hand, we lack of a measurement that corresponds temporally with the theories we have. While our explanations of state capacities are \emph{historical} in nature, in practice most available measurements capture \emph{contemporary} levels of stateness. In this paper I try to bridge this gap by providing an explanation of the origins of state capacities in Latin America and a corresponding indicator able to capture an \emph{historical measurement} of state capacities. This paper then seeks to contribute to the state formation literature in general, both from a theoretical and methodological perspectives. 

