% argument (2): fiscal system and sectoral conflicts
The expansion of the fiscal system has a long tradition of being associated with sectoral conflicts. For example, Schumpeter sees ``taxation in terms of group conflicts,''\footnote{\citet[14]{Monson2015}.} while others as ``an outcome of economic relations''\footnote{Seligman (1895). In \citet[7]{Martin2009a}.} Following this tradition, I sketch the theory around the sectoral conflicts between the industrial and agricultural elites in Latin America. Class conflicts are more likely to resolve in favor of direct taxation where income inequality \emph{among the elite} is low.\footnote{\citet[157]{Tani1966} explains that the absence of ``wealth groups'' makes passing an income tax law easier.} Given that similar degrees of sectoral economic development can be converted into armies with similar capabilities,\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}.} elites will have incentives to reach agreements rather than engage in conflict. And in the Latin American context, considering the initial institutional and economical advantages the agricultural sector enjoyed since the colonial period, reducing inter-elite inequality meant for the industrial sector to catch up with the agricultural sector. Elsewhere, I have argued that the emergence of a strong industrial elite altered not only the structure of the economy but also the inter-sectoral balance of political power, making unsustainable the political monopoly run by the landed elites.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.}


% argument (3): sectoral conflicts and state capacities
A sectoral theory focused on conflict offers a theory of the origins of state capacities as well. As others have argued, ``state formation will be more likely to the degree that powerful individual actors form two groups on the basis of divergent economic and political interests.''\footnote{\citet[1085]{Hechter1980a}.} Since state centralization affects landowners and industrialists in different ways, every sector will have different preferences about taxation and state centralization.\footnote{See \citet[289]{Acemoglu:1996rm} and \citet[50]{Best1976}.} Agriculturalists systematically resisted taxation as land fixity increased the risk premium of their main asset,\footnote{\citet[512]{Robinson2006a}.} while industrialists' preferences toward taxation were more elastic as capital could be reinvested in nontaxable sectors.\footnote{\citet[]{Hirschman:1970bl} and Ronald Rogowski in \citet[ch. 4]{Drake:1998pi}. However, see \citet[15]{Bates1985}.} 










The implementation of the tax required a secular accumulation of know-how, particularly, of technologies to monitor individual incomes. Observing individual economies and transforming private income into public property is what cases the state to develop further.\footnote{\citet[98]{Musgrave1992} and \citet[298]{Moore2004a}.} In fact, \citet[99]{Musgrave1992} argues that since taxation (specially on incomes) requires such a high degree of state penetration, public finances offer the key for a theory of state-building. It was Schumpeter who argued in favor of a systematic study of public finances, treating taxation both as cause (and consequence) of large-scale changes in the structure of the state.\footnote{Martin et al. (in \citet[2]{Martin2009a}).} Famously, he argued that `the budget is the skeleton of the state stripped of all misleading ideologies.'\footnote{\citet[100]{Schumpeter:1991yq}.} I contend that the expansion of the fiscal system, embodied specially in the income tax, contributed in an important way to the consolidation of the Latin American state. 





























